  "body_text": "IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON COMPUTER-AIDED DESIGN OF INTEGRATED CIRCUITS AND SYSTEMS, VOL. 44, NO. 11, NOVEMBER 2025\nA Heterogeneous CNN Compilation Framework\nfor RISC-V CPU and NPU Integration Based\non ONNX-MLIR\nShan Cao\n, Member, IEEE, Meiling Yang, Yintao Liu, Yu Li,\nBeining Zhao, Graduate Student Member, IEEE, Xinyu Chen, and Zhiyuan Jiang\n, Member, IEEE\nAbstract—With the continuous advancement of convolutional\nneural networks (CNNs), many neural network processing units\n(NPUs) have emerged in recent years. NPUs offer advantages,\nsuch as improved energy efﬁciency and low latency compared to\ntraditional processors. However, NPUs often struggle to keep pace\nwith the growing complexity of algorithmic models, which limits\nthe implementation of certain AI applications. Central processing\nunits (CPUs) are known for their versatility, but are computa-\ntionally inefﬁcient. Combining the strengths of both architectures\ncould present a viable solution to these challenges. Despite\nthis potential, there is currently insufﬁcient academic focus on\nCPU/NPU co-computing, and few architectures or toolchains\nhave been developed to support such integration. In this article,\nwe propose a RISC-V CPU/NPU co-computing-based compilation\nframework to solve the problem of mapping from algorithms\nto heterogeneous architectures. To bridge the computational\ngap between heterogeneous platforms, within ONNX-MLIR, we\ndeveloped three phases to support operator packing, algorithm\nadaption, and data coordination. To integrate heterogeneous\ncompilation platforms, we introduce four additional functions\nto handle task scheduling, weight quantization, weight rear-\nrangement, and memory management. In particular: 1) to\noptimize the transition overhead, an operator packing technique\nis introduced by extending the ONNX-MLIR framework with\ncustom operators, which enhances NPU efﬁciency by reducing\nthe number of transitions between operations; 2) at the aspect\nof task scheduling, a three-mode task scheduler is developed\nto allow users to customize task distribution for correctness\nveriﬁcation, performance optimization, or detailed analysis on\nheterogeneous platforms, which demonstrates the versatility of\nour framework; and 3) In terms of memory management, an\noptimized scheme for CPU/NPU architectures is proposed to\nensure accurate data access. This memory management employs\na dual-end approach with self-checks and a release-after-use\nmechanism to further improve efﬁciency. Experimental results\ndemonstrate that the framework effectively generates instructions\nfor various CNNs, signiﬁcantly enhancing the efﬁciency and\nperformance of heterogeneous architectures. It achieves up to a\nReceived 9 December 2024; revised 5 March 2025 and 14 April 2025;\naccepted 18 April 2025. Date of publication 25 April 2025; date of current\nversion 22 October 2025. This work was supported in part by the National\nNatural Science Foundation of China (NSFC) under Grant 62271300 and\nGrant 12141107, and in part by the Shanghai Science and Technology Plan\nProject under Grant 24DP1501100 and Grant 24DP1500600. This article was\nrecommended by Associate Editor T. Theocharides. (Corresponding author:\nShan Cao.)\nThe authors are with the Key Laboratory of Specialty Fiber Optics and\nOptical Access Networks, Joint International Research Laboratory of Specialty\nFiber Optics and Advanced Communication, Shanghai Institute for Advanced\nCommunication and Data Science, Shanghai University, Shanghai 200444,\nChina (e-mail: cshan@shu.edu.cn yimilier@shu.edu.cn; berialest@shu.edu.cn;\ncarrplee@shu.edu.cn;\nzbn@shu.edu.cn;\nchenxinyu5523@shu.edu.cn;\njiangzhiyuan@shu.edu.cn).\nDigital Object Identiﬁer 10.1109/TCAD.2025.3564561\n7.06× reduction in code density and up to a 5.58× improvement\nin memory usage, narrowing the computational gap between\nCPUs and NPUs.\nIndex Terms—Compilation framework, heterogeneous plat-\nform, neural processing unit (NPU), ONNX-MLIR, RISC-V.\nI. INTRODUCTION\nC\nONVOLUTIONAL neural networks (CNNs) have shown\nremarkable advantages in image processing and are\nextensively used in various artiﬁcial intelligence (AI) appli-\ncations, such as face recognition [1], object detection [2],\nand automatic driving [3]. However, as the scale and appli-\ncation scenario of these networks increases, CNNs introduce\nhigher computation capability and energy efﬁciency demands,\nexceeding the capabilities of central processing units (CPUs)\nand graphics processing units (GPUs). To address this growing\nneed, the design of efﬁcient processors speciﬁcally tailored for\nneural networks, known as neural processing units (NPUs),\nhas become essential.\nNPUs play a crucial role in the advancement of AI, offering\nbeneﬁts, such as low energy consumption, low latency, high\ncomputing efﬁciency, and programmability. However, NPU\ntends to be less generalizable due to design cost consider-\nations. They also struggle to keep pace with the increasing\ncomplexity of algorithmic models, limiting the implementa-\ntion of CNNs with diverse operators. Although CPUs are\nknown for their versatility, they suffer from low energy\nefﬁciency for data- and computation-intensive CNN inference\ntasks [4]. Therefore, a heterogeneous CPU/NPU platform is\nessential to perform multiple CNN inference computations\nwhile meeting performance and power constraints. However,\nthere is currently a lack of academic focus on CPU/NPU\nresearch, and few architectures or toolchains have been\ndeveloped to support co-computing between these two types of\nprocessors.\nOn the CPU side, the RISC-V architecture is gaining pop-\nularity in edge computing due to its open-source and modular\nnature. It allows ﬂexible selection of instruction subsets tai-\nlored to speciﬁc applications. For example, RV32IMC is used\nin [5] for low-power scenarios in small areas. Additionally,\nRISC-V reserves signiﬁcant instruction code space for user-\ndeﬁned extensions [6], [7], making it ideal for domain-speciﬁc\nenhancements. A notable example is RV-CNN, a domain-\nspeciﬁc instruction set with nine matrix instructions based\non the custom’ instruction in [7], which improves code\n1937-4151 c⃝2025 IEEE. All rights reserved, including rights for text and data mining, and training of artiﬁcial intelligence\nand similar technologies. Personal use is permitted, but republication/redistribution requires IEEE permission.\nSee https://www.ieee.org/publications/rights/index.html for more information.\nCAO et al.: HETEROGENEOUS CNN COMPILATION FRAMEWORK\ndensity while maintaining ﬂexibility and efﬁciency for CNNs.\nConsiderable academic work [8], [9] has explored mapping\nCNNs to RISC-V instructions, but most efforts focus on neural\nnetwork deployment rather than computational efﬁciency.\nThe ONNX-MLIR toolchain [10] is a modular, open-source\nframework that supports adaptive scaling, converting ONNX\ninput into multilevel intermediate representations (MLIRs).\nHowever, it currently lacks support for generating back-end\ninstructions for heterogeneous architectures.\nOn the NPU side, customization requirements necessitate\na dedicated CNN compiler for generating instructions. The\ncompilers of CNN accelerators serve as a bridge between hard-\nware and algorithms, optimizing network models based on the\ntarget hardware architecture. Compilation-level optimization\ntechniques, such as loop tiling [11], can help address the\nlimitations of network deployment imposed by hardware\nresource constraints. However, challenges remain, including\nunimplemented operators and unique architectures. These\nissues highlight the need for a heterogeneous computing\narchitecture that can integrate NPUs with other processing\nunits, enabling cross-architecture optimization and leveraging\nthe strengths of diverse hardware platforms.\nDifferent hardware architectures often have their own\nunique instruction sets and capabilities. To integrate a\nheterogeneous compilation platform that supports multiple\narchitectures, it is essential to ensure that the generated code\nis compatible across all targeted devices. Many architec-\ntures [12], [13] designed for heterogeneous computing have\nemerged in recent years. Additionally, several architectures\nthat exhibit heterogeneous-like characteristics have been intro-\nduced [14], [15]. However, these architectures often support\nonly a limited number of CNNs and uses the CPU solely as\na host, without incorporating it into the computation process.\nThis limitation restricts the potential for extending generality\nin these systems.\nTo address the aforementioned issues, this article presents\na versatile compilation framework built upon the RISC-V\nCPU and NPU co-computing architecture. This framework\nis designed to efﬁciently map algorithms to heterogeneous\narchitectures. As illustrated in Fig. 1, it accepts a pruned\nand quantized ONNX format ﬁle as input, and integrates a\ncustom CNN compiler with the open-source ONNX-MLIR\ntoolchain. Following this, decision-making processes and\nvarious optimization techniques are applied to generate the\ncorresponding RISC-V instruction set architecture (ISA) and\nNPU ISA for implementation on the heterogeneous archi-\ntecture. The main contributions of this work include the\nfollowing.\n1) By extending the ONNX-MLIR framework with custom\noperators, we introduce an operator packing technique\nthat maximizes the computational efﬁciency of NPUs,\nwhile minimizing overhead during transitions between\nheterogeneous operations.\n2) A task scheduler with three operational modes is\ndeveloped, allowing users to customize the task dis-\ntribution according to speciﬁc requirements, including\ncorrectness veriﬁcation, performance optimization, or\ndetailed analysis of computational workﬂows across\nFig. 1.\nIllustration of the heterogeneous compilation framework and its\ninterfaces toward external tools, with details on the components extended for\nthe generation of heterogeneous instructions.\nheterogeneous platforms, which typically emphasizes\nthe versatility of the framework.\n3) The discrete memory allocation strategy is optimized to\naccommodate the CPU/NPU heterogeneous architecture,\nensuring seamless data access during cross-platform\ncomputations. To further enhance memory efﬁciency,\nthe memory management system incorporates two tech-\nniques: a dual-end (DE) allocation strategy with a\nself-check function, and a release-after-use (RU) mech-\nanism that minimizes memory footprint.\nThe remainder of the article is structured as follows. The\nrelated works are listed in Section II. In Section III, the\nbackgrounds of the framework are introduced; in Section IV,\nthe overview of our heterogeneous compilation framework\nis presented. Within ONNX-MLIR optimizations, including\noperator packing, algorithm adaption, and data coordination\nare presented in Section V. Section VI illustrates four func-\ntions to seamlessly integrate the heterogeneous compilation.\nThe thorough evaluation of the framework and technologies is\ndescribed and analyzed in Section VII, and the whole work is\nsummarized in Section VIII.\nII. RELATED WORKS\nThe rise of heterogeneous computing introduces signiﬁ-\ncant challenges in mapping workloads to diverse hardware\naccelerators, particularly under resource-constrained environ-\nments. Previous works have explored various partitioning and\noptimization strategies to efﬁciently allocate computations\nacross different processing units.\nTVM [16] is an open-source compiler framework that\napplies multilevel IR optimizations for deploying models on\nIEEE TRANSACTIONS ON COMPUTER-AIDED DESIGN OF INTEGRATED CIRCUITS AND SYSTEMS, VOL. 44, NO. 11, NOVEMBER 2025\nvarious hardware backends. Its abstraction layers, Relay and\nTIR, enable hardware-speciﬁc code generation but do not\nsupport cross-device collaboration. TensorRT, developed by\nNVIDIA, is widely used for GPU inference and applies\ngraph-level optimizations, such as layer fusion and precision\ncalibration. However, like TVM, it mainly targets single-\naccelerator deployment and lacks native support for CPU/NPU\ncooperative execution.\nCurzel et al. [14] introduced a compilation toolchain sim-\nilar to ONNX-MLIR but incorporate high-level synthesis\ntechniques on the backend to generate efﬁcient accelerators.\nThis approach provides an effective means of improving\nhardware efﬁciency by optimizing computation at the design\nstage. Liu et al. [13] presented a CPU/FPGA/NPU hetero-\ngeneous system for UAV applications, utilizing the uniﬁed\nprogramming language DPC++ [17] to streamline develop-\nment across diverse computing platforms. This demonstrates\nthe efﬁciency of heterogeneous architectures in specialized\nscenarios. Similarly, Qin et al. [12] introduced a CNN\nhardware accelerator within a RISC-V-based heterogeneous\nsystem, speciﬁcally designed for YOLOv3-Tiny. Their work\nshowcases a well-optimized hardware-software co-design for\ndeep learning inference. NEST-C [18] is a deep learning\ncompiler framework that enhances model deployment and\nperformance across AI accelerators. It employs proﬁling-based\nquantization, dynamic graph partitioning, and multilevel IR\nintegration for efﬁcient execution on heterogeneous hardware.\nAdditionally, it features PartitionTuner [19], an operator sched-\nuler that optimally distributes workloads across CPUs, NPUs,\nand other processing units to minimize inference time.\nOverall,\nthese\nworks\ncontribute\nsigniﬁcantly\nto\nthe\nﬁeld of heterogeneous computing by introducing effective\noptimization strategies, compilation techniques, and hardware-\nsoftware co-design methods. Building on these efforts, our\nwork focuses on a ﬂexible and generalizable framework\nthat leverages ONNX-MLIR’s multilevel dialect structure for\nefﬁcient task partitioning and resource management, enabling\nbroader applicability across various CNN models and hetero-\ngeneous computing scenarios.\nIII. PRELIMINARIES\nMapping CNNs to heterogeneous architectures involves\nleveraging two key techniques. First, ONNX-MLIR generates\nvalid instructions for CNN operators on RISC-V and produces\nintermediate representations at multiple levels, which enhances\nthe ability to manage various tasks effectively. Second, the\nRISC-V instruction extension plays a crucial role in enabling\nthe integration of heterogeneous instructions.\nA. ONNX-MLIR Toolchain\nONNX is a widely used standard that enables seamless AI\nmodel transfer between frameworks like PyTorch [20] and\nTensorFlow [21], facilitating efﬁcient transitions from research\nto production. Before deployment, models often undergo\noptimization techniques, such as pruning [22] and quanti-\nzation [23]. Researchers apply these optimizations across\ndifferent frameworks and export the reﬁned models in ONNX\nformat for implementation. Additionally, ONNX ﬁles are\nhighly readable and accessible via the “protoc” command or\nvisualization tools like “netron.”\nMLIR [24] is an extensible IR supporting various abstrac-\ntion\nlevels,\nfrom\nhigh-level\nalgorithmic\ndescriptions\nto\nlow-level instruction sets. It provides tools for static type\nchecking, code veriﬁcation, and optimization, ensuring efﬁ-\ncient target code generation. The ONNX-MLIR project\nincludes three dialect levels: 1) ONNX; 2) MLIR; and\n3) LLVM. With its mature I/O interfaces and ﬂexible IRs,\nwe use ONNX-MLIR as the foundation of our heterogeneous\ncompilation framework for mapping CNNs to RISC-V instruc-\ntions.\nAn ONNX ﬁle can be converted into the ONNX dialect,\nwhich offers high readability and aids in heterogeneous task\ndecisions. It separates constant inputs for each network layer,\nfacilitating parameter organization and optimization. Each\nrow represents a network layer, containing all necessary\ncomputation parameters, which are useful for both instruction\ngeneration and task assignment between CPU and NPU. The\nMLIR dialect expresses operations as loop-based computa-\ntions, enabling optimizations like tiling and unrolling [25].\nFinally, the LLVM dialect handles memory allocation and\nutilizes low-level “llvm” functions, making it well-suited for\naddress reassignment in heterogeneous architectures.\nB. RISC-V Instruction Extension\nIn the standard encoding format of RISC-V, there are\nthree “reserved” and four “custom” opcodes designated for\ninstruction extension, all preﬁxed with “11” (in bit 1:0 of\nthe instruction), effectively offering a signiﬁcant amount of\nencoding space. Additionally, there are three 30-bit instruction\nencoding spaces, preﬁxed with “00,” “01,” and “10,” available\nfor optional compressed instruction extensions. However, if\nthe compressed instruction set extension is not required, these\nthree 30-bit encoding spaces can be repurposed for uses.\nFor instance, the “00” preﬁx could be used for a set of\ncustom vector operations to support enhanced functionality\nwithout expanding beyond the 32-bit format. Similarly, the\n“01” preﬁx could be used for a different class of extended\ninstructions, such as specialized arithmetic operations. This\napproach maximizes the encoding capacity of the RISC-\nV architecture, providing ﬂexibility for advanced instruction\nextensions without the immediate need for the compressed\ninstruction sets.\nIV. OVERVIEW OF COMPILATION FRAMEWORK\nA. Overview\nFig. 2(a) provides the overview of our heterogeneous\ncompilation framework. To bridge the computational gap\nbetween heterogeneous platforms, we developed three phases\nwithin ONNX-MLIR:\n1) operator packing; 2) algorithm\nadaptation; and 3) data coordination. Additionally, we intro-\nduce four functions to integrate heterogeneous compilation\nplatforms, including task scheduling, weight quantization,\nweight rearrangement, and memory management. Importantly,\nour framework considers hardware resource constraints and\nCAO et al.: HETEROGENEOUS CNN COMPILATION FRAMEWORK\n(a)\n(b)\n(c)\nFig. 2.\nOverview of heterogeneous compilation framework. (a) Workﬂow of our compilation framework. (b) Workﬂow of our previous NPU compiler,\nincluding translation, optimization, and execution. (c) Illustration of the MLIR.\nTABLE I\nHARDWARE AND SOFTWARE CONFIGURATION INPUT SUPPORTED\nBY THE COMPILATION FRAMEWORK\nincludes dynamic quantization at the software level, as detailed\nin Table I, which allows for high conﬁgurability.\nThe task scheduler takes the ONNX dialect as input,\npartitions tasks between the CPU and NPU based on hardware\nconstraints or other speciﬁc requirements. It then relays the\npartitioning results back to ONNX-MLIR for operator packing.\nAt the same time, the task scheduler outputs the NPU operators\nto the NPU compiler, enabling the mapping of these operators\nto NPU instructions.\nOperator packing involves grouping the partitioned oper-\nators into CPU and NPU functions, so that the instructions\nin the NPU functions can be subsequently replaced by\nthe corresponding NPU instructions. The NPU is not only\nconstrained by the types of operators it can compute but\nalso by the speciﬁc parameter limitations of each operator.\nFor example, many NPU architectures feature convolution\noperations with standard feature map (FM) sizes, which is\nnot required for CPUs. This difference necessitates algo-\nrithm adaptation between the two platforms. This approach\nnot only streamlines the data ﬂow between the CPU and\nNPU, but also facilitates more efﬁcient utilization of the\nNPU’s specialized capabilities. Although this adaptation intro-\nduces some computational overhead on the CPU side, it\nwill be shown that the beneﬁts far outweigh this minor\ncost.\nThe weight quantizer converts ﬂoating-point constants from\nthe NPU in the MLIR dialect into ﬁxed-point numbers based\non dynamic quantization parameters. The quantized data are\nthen combined with the layer parameters generated during the\noptimization phase of the CNN compiler to perform weight\nrearrangement, tailored to the hardware architecture. Finally,\nthe data is returned to the MLIR dialect and stored as “NPU\nconstants,” allowing us to retrieve the constant addresses for\neach layer during the generation phase.\nMoreover, performance considerations for the NPU archi-\ntecture result in differences in how FM data is stored between\nthe NPU and CPU. To address this, data coordination is inte-\ngrated within the MLIR dialect. Once this data is passed to the\nLLVM dialect, the memory manager uniﬁes the management\nof CPU and NPU data spaces, ensuring the correctness of data\naccess across layers while optimizing memory usage.\nTo ensure compatibility within a heterogeneous archi-\ntecture, each 512-bit NPU instruction must be split into\n18 individual 32-bit instructions in the RISC-V format. In\nthis conﬁguration, the “00” preﬁx is assigned to NPU-\nspeciﬁc instructions, while the “10” preﬁx indicates the ﬁnal\ninstruction in the sequence. This transformation enables the\nseamless integration of NPU instructions within the RISC-V\narchitecture.\nB. NPU Compiler\nThe NPU compiler in the heterrogeneous compiliation\nframework is based on our previous work [11], designed for\nthe NPU in [26]. The compilation process consists of three\nIEEE TRANSACTIONS ON COMPUTER-AIDED DESIGN OF INTEGRATED CIRCUITS AND SYSTEMS, VOL. 44, NO. 11, NOVEMBER 2025\nphases: 1) translation; 2) optimization; and 3) generation, as\nshown in Fig. 2(b).\nIn the translation phase, network layers are analyzed via\ntext matching and categorized into ﬁve operation types:\n1) convolution; 2) fully connected (FC) layers; 3) pooling;\n4) concatenation; and 5) element addition. The model is then\nconverted into an intermediate format [Format 2 in Fig. 2(c)],\ncontaining only essential parameters, such as operation types,\nlayer details, and special layer identiﬁers.\nDuring optimization, the network model is reorganized\nthrough techniques like layer fusion and splitting to better\nﬁt the accelerator. A compiler-level loop tiling method is\nintroduced to divide large layers into smaller ones, reducing\nstorage and memory access demands. Additionally, weight and\nbias data are reordered alongside layer splitting.\nIn the generation phase, the ﬁnal CNN representation, along\nwith weight and bias data, is produced for the accelerator.\nData is reordered per the accelerator’s requirements [27], and\nadditional parameters are computed. PE mask bits are also\ndeployed to support padding, stride, and dilation operations,\nenhancing accelerator versatility.\nC. GUI for Compilation Framework\nTo fully emphasize the versatility of our framework, we\nhave developed a graphical user interface (GUI) to enhance\nuser experience and meet on-demand needs. At the algorithmic\nlevel, our compilation framework supports a wide range\nof CNNs, including the Resnet series, VGG [28] series,\nMobileNet [29] series, and more. Additionally, users can fully\ncustomize all hardware conﬁgurations, as outlined in Table I.\nEspecially for quantization format, our architecture supports\na variety of data types for different backends. Depending on\nthe application scenario, users can specify whether the CPU\nshould compute in ﬂoating point or use the same data type as\nthe NPU. Furthermore, users can input the optimal ﬁxed-point\nparameters generated by the upper-level quantization platform\nthrough user-deﬁned conﬁgurations.\nBeyond the default task division strategy, where all NPU-\nimplementable operators are designated as NPU tasks, users\ncan opt for all-CPU computation to verify the correctness of\nNPU operations. In addition to this, users can manually specify\nthe division of tasks by entering a set of binary numbers: “0”\nfor CPU tasks and “1” for NPU tasks, making it easy to com-\npare the acceleration effects of different hardware platforms.\nThis functionality can also be achieved by modifying the\n“implementable operators,” which simpliﬁes the exploration of\nacceleration effects for speciﬁc classes of operators, including\nthe associated constraints.\nV. OPTIMIZATION WITHIN ONNX-MLIR\nBased on the architecture in Fig. 2, we have developed three\nphases within ONNX-MLIR to optimize dialects, enhancing\nthe convergence of heterogeneous platforms.\nA. Operator Packing\nA key technique for effectively leveraging the capabilities of\nNPUs is CNN operator packing within the MLIR framework.\nIn the MLIR ecosystem, CNN operator packing involves\nencapsulating multiple operations into composite ones, which\ncan be mapped more efﬁciently to NPU instructions. The\nprimary goal is to streamline the execution of CNN models by\nreplacing these packed operators with highly optimized NPU\ninstructions during inference. This approach reduces the over-\nhead associated with individual operations, and maximizes the\nparallelism and specialized capabilities of NPUs, signiﬁcantly\naccelerating inference times.\n1) Adding Custom Operators to the Framework: To ensure\neffective instruction substitutions, our custom operators should\nbe added to the ONNX-MLIR toolchain before completing the\noperator packing. This process necessitates careful considera-\ntion of the target dialects and their interaction [10].\nThe ﬁrst step in extending ONNX-MLIR is to deﬁne new\noperators within the ONNX dialect. This process involves\nspecifying the name, inputs, outputs, and attributes of the oper-\nator according to the existing ONNX schema. The operator\nmust then be registered with the ONNX dialect to ensure it\nis recognized and correctly parsed by the compiler. Once the\noperator is deﬁned in the ONNX dialect, the next step is to\nlower it to the MLIR dialect. It involves transforming the high-\nlevel operation into a form that can be optimized. Finally,\nthe operator is lowered to the LLVM dialect and the newly\nadded operator should be compatible with the LLVM backend,\nensuring that it can be compiled into efﬁcient machine code\nfor the target architecture.\nIn the proposed heterogeneous compilation framework, the\ninstruction generation for the NPU takes place outside of\nthe ONNX-MLIR toolchain. As a result, the packed operator\ndoes not need to characterize either the operator information\nor the parameter information within the operator. However,\nit is important to ensure that the input and output variable\ninformation is preserved to prevent optimization during dialect\ntransfer. Therefore, following the steps for adding new oper-\nators and considering our speciﬁc requirements, three new\noperators are added to the ONNX dialect.\n1) %L1\n=\n“onnx.I3O1OfNPU”(%L0,\n%w1,\n%b1)\nfunc_name\n=\n@I3O1OfNPU0\n:\n(tensor<*>,\ntensor<*>, tensor<*>) -> tensor<*>\n2) %L2\n=\n“onnx.I4O1OfNPU”(%L1,\n%w2,\n%b2,\n%L0) func_name = @I4O1OfNPU0 : (tensor<*>,\ntensor<*>, tensor<*>, tensor<*>) -> tensor<*>\n3) %L3\n=\n“onnx.I1O1OfNPU”(%L2)\nfunc_name\n=\n@I1O1OfNPU0 : (tensor<*>) -> tensor<*>.\nAs outlined above, we classify NPU operators into three\ntypes based on input and output count, with their optimization\nhandled within the CNN compiler. In ONNX-MLIR, particu-\nlarly at the MLIR and LLVM dialect stages, the key task is to\naccurately transmit the corresponding wrapper function names.\nThis enables correct recognition and use of the operators\nduring ﬁnal compilation, eliminating the need for further\noptimization in these stages. Delegating optimization to the\nCNN compiler simpliﬁes NPU integration and improves the\nefﬁciency and scalability of the deployment pipeline.\n2) Intermediate Steps in Operator Packing: Fig. 3 illus-\ntrates the intermediate steps involved in operator packing.\nTaking\nthe\nclassic\nMNIST\nnetwork\nas\nan\nexample,\nCAO et al.: HETEROGENEOUS CNN COMPILATION FRAMEWORK\n(a)\n(b)\n(c)\n(d)\nFig. 3.\nIntermediate steps in operator packing, mapping from CNN models to hardware. (a) Input computational graph of the MNIST network represented in\nONNX. (b) Lowering high-Level ONNX operations to the ONNX dialect in MLIR (simpliﬁed). (c) Format of the ONNX dialect after searching and operator\npacking. (d) Final distribution of operations across the CPU and NPU.\nFig. 3(a) shows the input computational graph of the model\nexpressed in ONNX. This graph consists of a sequence of\noperations, including Maxpool, Reshape, two instances of\ngeneral matrix multiplication (Gemm), ReLU, and Softmax.\nFig. 3(b) depicts the lowering process within the ONNX-\nMLIR compiler, where the high-level ONNX operations are\nmapped to the ONNX dialect in MLIR. In this intermediate\nrepresentation, the operations are expressed as function calls,\npreserving the structure of the original computational graph.\nThis step serves as the initial phase of the compilation process,\npreparing the operations for further optimization and eventual\ntranslation to hardware-speciﬁc dialects.\nAfter conducting a search and operator packing, certain\noperations, such as Gemm and ReLU, have been consolidated\ninto NPU functions (e.g., NPU0 and NPU1), as illustrated in\nFig 3(c). Other operations, including Maxpool and Reshape,\nhave been assigned into CPU functions. Following the\ndownward mapping process, these operations are ultimately\ndistributed across various processing units, encompassing both\nCPU and NPU, as illustrated in Fig 3(d). For instance, some\noperations are executed on the CPU (e.g., CPU0 and CPU1),\nwhile others are ofﬂoaded to the NPU. The system bus\nfacilitates communication between these processing units and\nmemory, ensuring efﬁcient data transfer and processing across\ndifferent hardware components.\n3) Packing Strategy: For operations intended to be exe-\ncuted on the CPU, adjacent operators are grouped together into\na single CPU function. This strategy minimizes the overhead\nrelated to function calls and data transfers between opera-\ntions, thereby enhancing computational efﬁciency [30]. By\nconsolidating CPU-bound operations, the framework ensures\nmore effective utilization of the resources on the CPU, which\nreduces the latency and improves the overall performance.\nFor operations intended for execution on the NPU, operator\npacking is to maximize the throughput of the NPU by aligning\nthe operations with its speciﬁc instructions. This packing strat-\negy takes into consideration the capacity of NPU to efﬁciently\nhandle composite operations. Three main combinations of\noperators are considered for NPU packing.\n1) CONV\n+\n(ReLU/LeakyReLU/MaxPool/Average-Pool/\nConcat): By packing these operations together, the NPU\ncan process them in a streamlined manner, minimizing\nthe need for intermediate data transfers and reloading of\noperands.\n2) CONV\n+\nAdd\n+\n(ReLU/LeakyReLU/MaxPool/\nAveragePool/Concat): When a convolutional operation\nis followed by an element-wise addition (Add) and\nthen an activation or pooling operation, combining\nthese steps into a single NPU function can signiﬁcantly\nimprove execution efﬁciency. This approach is especially\nadvantageous in layers that include residual connections,\nsuch as in ResNet [31] architectures, where the addition\noperations are commonly utilized.\n3) GEMM + (ReLU/LeakyReLU/Reshape/Flatten): Similar\nas Convolution, by grouping these operations, the NPU\ncan handle them as a single unit. This is essential\nfor maintaining high throughput in the dense layers of\nneural networks.\nThis operator packing strategy optimizes the use of com-\nputational resources across CPUs and NPUs while reducing\noverhead during transitions between operations. By aligning\nthe packing process with the instruction-level execution of the\nNPU, this approach maximizes hardware utilization, leading\nto faster inference times and more efﬁcient execution of neural\nnetworks on heterogeneous systems.\nB. Algorithm Adaption\nDespite their computational efﬁciency, NPUs often face\nhardware-speciﬁc limitations regarding the types of operations\nthey can perform and the parameters they support. These\nconstraints necessitate careful consideration when adapting\nalgorithms for integration with more ﬂexible CPU-based\nplatforms.\nFirst, on most NPUs, convolutional computations are opti-\nmized for FMs sizes that are powers of two (e.g., 32 ×\n16 × 16, 128 × 32 × 32). This limitation stems from the\ninternal architecture of NPU, which is designed to maximize\nparallelism and memory access efﬁciency when handling data\nIEEE TRANSACTIONS ON COMPUTER-AIDED DESIGN OF INTEGRATED CIRCUITS AND SYSTEMS, VOL. 44, NO. 11, NOVEMBER 2025\nFig. 4.\nData coordination in the MLIR dialect involves modifying the CPU’s FM storage order to match that of the NPU. This algorithm implements a\nﬁxed-point quantization of the input FM.\nof speciﬁc sizes. In contrast, CPUs do not impose such\nstrict limitations on FM sizes, allowing for greater ﬂexibility\nin executing convolutional operations. This discrepancy in\noperational parameters between NPUs and CPUs presents\na signiﬁcant challenge when attempting to deploy neural\nnetworks across heterogeneous platforms that incorporate both\ntypes of processors.\nOne effective strategy to address this challenge is to use the\npadding [32] and reshaping techniques to conform non-power-\nof-2 FMs to NPU-compatible sizes. This process involves\npadding the FMs with zeros or other values to expand their\ndimensions to the nearest power of 2, thus enabling efﬁcient\nprocessing on the NPU. Notably, padding is only required\nin the row and channel dimensions. After the processing is\ncomplete, any extraneous padding can be removed or adjusted\nto restore the original dimensions of the FM before transferring\nthe data back to the CPU or subsequent layers in the neural\nnetwork. To minimize additional design overheads, we modify\nCPU computations to align with NPU processing.\nSecond, heterogeneous platforms often face challenges with\ninconsistent accuracy. Typically, CPUs use double-precision\n(64-bit) ﬂoating-point arithmetic, whereas NPUs may utilize\nreduced precision formats, such as 16-bit or even 8-bit integer\nrepresentations [33]. This shift to lower precision on NPUs\ncan lead to rounding errors and diminished accuracy in com-\nputations, which may result in discrepancies when compared\nto the results produced by CPUs.\nAt the compiler level, there are two primary approaches to\naddress this issue. First, we can introduce inverse ﬁxed-point\nquantization operators before CPU functions and ﬁxed-point\nquantization operators after them. This process allows CPU\noperators to perform pseudo-ﬁxed-point computation, which\ncan enhance accuracy to some extent. Second, it is also\npossible to convert all CPU operators directly to ﬁxed-\npoint computation, which improves computational efﬁciency.\nHowever, certain operators in ONNX, such as Softmax, do\nnot support direct ﬁxed-point computation [34]. In these\ncases, the ﬁrst method becomes necessary. In our compilation\nframework, both methods are implemented, allowing users\nthe ﬂexibility to choose the approach that best suits their\napplication scenario.\nC. Data Coordination\nAside from the possible differences in FM sizes, the order\nin which the FMs are arranged may also vary. Typically, CPUs\nemploy row-major storage to optimize memory access patterns\nand enhance cache utilization. Conversely, NPUs often use\noptimized orders, such as channel-major or block-major to\nenhance parallel processing efﬁciency [35]. This difference in\nordering requires data rearrangement when it is transferred\nbetween the CPU and NPU, which increases the overhead\nof memory accesses and introduces additional latency, which\nultimately impacts the overall performance.\nVarious strategies have been proposed to optimize FM\nlayouts on heterogeneous platforms, including automatic lay-\nout transformation [16], hardware-aware neural architecture\nsearch [36], custom compiler passes, and so on. Given the high\ncost of altering hardware design, we have chosen to modify\nthe CPU’s FM storage order to align with that of the NPU.\nThe operation is translated into a loop-based computation in\nthe MLIR dialect, allowing for data coordination for CPU\noperators, as shown in Fig. 4. Our NPU platform employs\nthe channel-major computation, in which the order of the\nFMs is speciﬁed as [col, channel, row], requiring us to swap\nthe intra-CPU column dimension with the channel dimension.\nOur method effectively allows for seamless data coordination\nacross heterogeneous platforms with minimal code changes\nand negligible overhead, as illustrated in Fig. 4.\nVI. INTEGRATION OF HETEROGENEOUS\nCOMPILATION PLATFORM\nHeterogeneous compilation platforms vary in their inputs\nand outputs, optimization methods, memory allocation, and\nmore. To integrate these platforms seamlessly, we developed\nfour functions that focus on task scheduling, weight quantizer,\nweight reorderer, and memory management across both plat-\nforms.\nA. Task Scheduler\nIn the task scheduling strategy for heterogeneous systems,\nthree modes are provided, as outlined in Algorithm 1, to\nmanage the assignment of operations between the CPU and\nthe NPU according to the user-speciﬁc requirements.\n1) All_CPU Mode: In certain situations, users may wish\nto verify the correctness of the computations performed on the\nNPU by comparing them with results obtained from the CPU.\nTo facilitate this, the algorithm offers an ALL_CPU mode,\nwhich forces all tasks to be executed on the CPU, regardless of\ntheir compatibility with the NPU. This approach guarantees a\nconsistent computational environment for accuracy validation.\nCAO et al.: HETEROGENEOUS CNN COMPILATION FRAMEWORK\nAlgorithm 1 Task Scheduling of CPU/NPU Operators\nInput: CM: calculation mode, OD: ONNX dialect, NO:\nnumber of operators, (TD: task designation, NR: NPU\nrestrictions);\nOutput: TC: task of CPU, TN: task of NPU;\n1: for each i ∈[1, NO] do\n2:\nif CM == ALL_CPU then\n3:\nAdd current operator to TC\n4:\nelse if CM == USER_DEFINE then\n5:\nif TD[i] == cpu then\n6:\nAdd current operator to TC\n7:\nelse if TD[i] == npu then\n8:\nAdd current operator to TN\n9:\nend if\n10:\nelse if CM == DEFAULT then\n11:\nif OD[i] meets NR then\n12:\nAdd current operator to TN\n13:\nelse\n14:\nAdd current operator to TC\n15:\nend if\n16:\nend if\n17: end for\n18: return TC, TN\n2) USER_DEFINE Mode: For advanced users seeking\nmanual control over task distribution between the CPU and\nNPU, the scheduler supports a USER_DEFINE mode. In this\nmode, users can specify a binary string for task designation\n(denoted as TD), where each bit indicates the assignment of an\noperator: “0” for CPU and “1” for NPU. This feature allows\nusers to experiment with various conﬁgurations, enabling the\nevaluation of the hardware platform in acceleration capabilities\nand a thorough comparison of performance between the CPU\nand NPU.\n3) DEFAULT Mode: By default, the scheduler assigns\ntasks based on the capabilities of the NPU. It checks whether\neach operation meets the NPU’s restrictions. If an operator is\ncompatible with the NPU, it is added to the NPU task list\n(TN). Otherwise, it is assigned to the CPU task list (TC). This\nstrategy optimizes performance by leveraging the calculation\ncapacity of NPUs for suitable tasks.\nIn this mode, the scheduler allows users to modify the\nlist of “implementable operators” that determines which tasks\ncan be processed by the NPU. By adjusting these settings,\nusers can explore the performance impact of speciﬁc classes\nof operations on the NPU, while considering any associated\nconstraints. This level of customization is especially valuable\nfor researchers and engineers seeking to optimize speciﬁc\ncomputational workloads.\nThe algorithm begins by iterating over all operators from the\nONNX dialect (OD). Depending on the selected calculation\nmode (CM), it applies the appropriate task assignment logic.\nOnce all operators are processed, the algorithm returns two\nlists, TC, representing the tasks allocated to the CPU, and TD,\nrepresenting the tasks allocated to the NPU. This structured\nand ﬂexible approach allows users to tailor task distribution\nbased on their speciﬁc needs, whether it involves correctness\nveriﬁcation, performance optimization, or in-depth analysis of\ncomputational workﬂows on heterogeneous platforms.\nB. Weight Quantizer and Reorderer\nThe weight quantizer and reorderer are fundamental com-\nponents in the optimization pipeline for deploying CNNs on\nNPUs. This process ensures that the weight parameters of\nneural networks are efﬁciently formatted and optimized for\nthe speciﬁc hardware architecture of the NPU, enhancing\nperformance and reducing computational overhead. On top of\nthat, if ﬁxed-point computation is to be performed on the CPU,\nthe weights must also be quantized. The overall process can\nbe divided into several key stages.\n1) Weight Quantization: The ﬁrst step involves the weight\nquantizer, which converts ﬂoating-point constant data in the\nMLIR dialect into ﬁxed-point data. This conversion applies to\nboth NPU operators and CPU operators that require ﬁxed-point\ncomputation. The conversion process is guided by dynamic\nquantization parameters, which are determined based on the\nstatistical properties of the data from the upper quantization\nplatform. Dynamic quantization [37] enables adaptive scaling\nof weights, ensuring that the ﬁxed-point representation pre-\nserves the necessary precision while minimizing quantization\nerrors.\n2) Integration With NPU Optimized Layer Parameters:\nAfter quantization, the next step is to integrate the quan-\ntized data with the layer parameters produced during the\noptimization phase of the compiler. This phase introduces\ncompiler-level loop tiling, which may result in a different\nnumber of layers and associated parameters compared to the\noriginal network. The rearrangement of weights [11] is tailored\nto the speciﬁc architecture of the NPU, ensuring that the\nweights are organized in a manner that maximizes memory\naccess efﬁciency and computational throughput.\n3) Storing Quantized and Rearranged Weights: After quan-\ntization and rearrangement, the processed weight data is\nconverted back into the MLIR dialect. This step ensures\nthat the data remains within a standardized and ﬂexible\nintermediate representation, which is compatible with the\nsubsequent stages of the compilation and deployment pipeline.\nThe quantized and rearranged weights are stored as “NPU\nconstants,” making it easier to retrieve their memory addresses\nduring the generation phase of the compilation process.\nC. Memory Manager\nHeterogeneous architectures that involve both CPUs and\nNPUs present complex challenges in memory allocation.\nOn the software side, CPUs utilize well-established memory\nallocation mechanisms, such as the stack, which operates as a\nlast-in, ﬁrst-out (LIFO) data structure [38]. On the hardware\nside, there are two common memory optimization methods,\nincluding the DE and RU mechanisms.\nThe DE mechanism [39] traverses the overall storage space\nof the input FM data and output FM data across all layers, and\nthen sets the maximum value as the current FM storage space.\nThis method is particularly effective for networks without\nIEEE TRANSACTIONS ON COMPUTER-AIDED DESIGN OF INTEGRATED CIRCUITS AND SYSTEMS, VOL. 44, NO. 11, NOVEMBER 2025\n(a)\n(b)\nFig. 5.\nCommon NPU memory optimization methods. (a) Bottleneck\nof ResNet50 (Stage 1 BTNK 2, original input FM size is 224×224×3);\n(b) read-write conﬂicts in DE memory management mechanism; (c) memory\nmanagement mechanism for RU.\nbranches or for architectures utilizing in-place algorithms to\nminimize memory usage. However, in certain architectures\nwith read-write concurrency or in networks with branches,\nthis approach can lead to read-write conﬂicts. For example,\nin Fig. 5(a), the bottleneck (Stage 1 BTNK 2) of Resnet50 is\npresented with an original input FM size of 224 ×224 ×3.\nFig. 5(b) illustrates the corresponding DE mechanism. At\nthe end of the NPU2 calculation, the output FM of NPU1\nis released. However, while calculating NPU3, a read-write\nconﬂict occurs due to insufﬁcient setup space, resulting in an\nerror in the result of NPU3.\nTo address the above issue, we designed a self-check\nfunction to simulate memory allocation and adjust initial\nmemory sizes upon data conﬂicts. Additionally, we intro-\nduced the RU mechanism [Fig. 5(c)], which, unlike the DE\nmechanism, avoids precomputing memory size or using self-\nchecks. It releases memory only after conﬁrming that no\nfuture operations require a speciﬁc layer’s FM. For example,\nin Fig. 5(c), NPU1 allocates memory for its output, while\nNPU0’s memory remains reserved due to dependencies from\nNPU3. Memory is released only after all related computations\nare complete, preventing data conﬂicts and ensuring reliable\nmemory management.\nIn a CPU/NPU heterogeneous system, memory allocation\ncan generally be categorized into two types: 1) uniﬁed memory\nand 2) discrete memory. Uniﬁed memory allows both the\nCPU and NPU to access a shared memory space, simplifying\nthe programming model by eliminating the need for explicit\ndata transfers between the CPU and NPU. However, this\nmodel may introduce challenges related to memory bandwidth\nand contention, as both processors compete for the same\nresources. In contrast, discrete memory allocation assigns\nAlgorithm 2 Memory Management of SW/HW Operators\nInput: network_nodes, START_HW: start address of hardware,\nMECH: mechanism of memory allocation\nOutput: nodes_raddr: read address of nodes, nodes_waddr: write\naddress of nodes\n1: Initialization: fmSet, DE_END: end address of the DE mecha-\nnism, RU_END: end address of the RU mechanism\n2: //determine the ofm of the memory to be allocated;\n3: for node in network_nodes do\n4:\nif node.type = SW then\n5:\nif nextnode.type = HW then\n6:\nfmSet.insert(node)\n7:\nend if\n8:\nelse if node.type = HW && node.input = ori_FM then\n9:\nfmSet.insert(ori_FM)\n10:\nelse if node.type = HW then\n11:\nfmSet.insert(node)\n12:\nend if\n13: end for\n14: //two memory allocation mechanisms (optional);\n15: if MECH = RU then\n16:\nnodes_waddr, RU_END = fmSet.RU(START_HW)\n17: else\n18:\n//self-checking for dual-end mechanism;\n19:\nDE_END = max(fmSet.ifm + fmSet.ofm)\n20:\nDE_END = fmSet.self_check(DE_END)\n21:\nnodes_waddr = fmSet.DE(DE_END, START_HW)\n22: end if\n23: for node in network_nodes do\n24:\nif (node.type = SW && prenode.type = HW) ∥(node.type =\nHW) then\n25:\nnodes_raddr = nodes_waddr.ﬁnd(node.ifm)\n26:\nend if\n27: end for\n28: return nodes_raddr, nodes_waddr\nseparate memory spaces for the CPU and NPU. While this\napproach can be more complex to manage because it requires\nexplicit data transfers between the memory of CPU and the\nmemory of NPU, it can offer more control.\nIn our work, we chose to use discrete memory allocation.\nAlgorithm 2 outlines the memory management process of\nhardware/software (HW/SW) operators. The memory manager\ntakes as input a set of nodes and the start address of the\nNPU memory (START_HW), and it outputs the read and write\naddresses of these nodes. It is noteworthy that only the last\nlayer of CPU and all NPU operators require memory allocation\n(or FM that inputs to NPU directly). This means that all FMs\nneeded by the NPU, both input and output, are allocated within\nthe NPU address segment. As a result, the read address of the\nﬁrst operator in the CPU function and the write address of the\nlast operator are explicitly deﬁned. In the LLVM dialect, we\ncreated a malloc_NPU function to enable the CPU to access\nthe NPU address segment.\nVII. EXPERIMENT AND EVALUATION\nTo validate the effectiveness of the proposed heterogeneous\ncompilation framework, a series of experiments are conducted,\nfocusing on versatility, speed up, and memory efﬁciency. The\nexperimental setup is as follows.\nSoftware Implementation: Our heterogeneous compilation\nframework is based on the ONNX-MLIR toolchain, and the\nCAO et al.: HETEROGENEOUS CNN COMPILATION FRAMEWORK\nTABLE II\nIMPLEMENTATION RESULTS OF THE PROPOSED HETEROGENEOUS COMPILATION FRAMEWORK COMPARED WITH STATE-OF-THE-ART COMPILERS\nimplementation of heterogeneous expansion, including the\nCNN compiler, is carried out using Python 3. The trained\nmodels in the ONNX format and various HW/SW settings are\ntaken as input. The output is divided into two parts: 1) the\ngenerated heterogeneous instructions as a hex ﬁle and 2) the\noriginal CPU parameters, along with the rearranged network\nparameters for NPU, stored as a binary ﬁle in DDR.\nHardware Platforms: The heterogeneous hardware archi-\ntecture is composed of a RISC-V CPU and a self-developed\nNPU. We choose the RV32IM instruction set for the RISC-V\nCPU, which features an 8 KB L1 cache. The NPU is\nimplemented by SMIC 40 nm CMOS technology, working\nat the clock frequency of 200 MHz. It supports commonly\nused operations in CNNs, such as convolution, FC, pooling,\netc. To comprehensively evaluate performance, we compare\nour results with state-of-the-art studies to measure network\ninference latency.\nNetwork Benchmarks: To evaluate the compilation frame-\nwork across various CNN networks, it is important to cover\ndifferent operators and architectures. For depth-based design,\nVGG and ResNet are classic models. VGG uses a straight-\nforward stack of 3 ×3 convolutions [28], while ResNet\nintroduces residual connections to address the vanishing gra-\ndient problem [31]. RepVGG [40] builds on VGG’s simplicity\nwith a reparameterization technique that improves infer-\nence efﬁciency while preserving model depth. For multiscale\ndesign, YOLO [41] supports multiscale detection, and its tiny\nversion is smaller, faster, and ideal for real-time tasks on\nresource-limited devices. To further demonstrate the generality\nof our framework, we also include a typical deep neural\nnetwork (DNN), MNIST, which features the widely-used\nGemm operator.\nA. Performance Evaluation\nAs mainstream frameworks, such as TVM and TensorRT do\nnot support our heterogeneous hardware or report comparable\nmetrics, we instead compare our method with representative\nworks [12], [13], [14], [18] that share similar architectural\nassumptions or compilation goals. We note that the reference\nworks used for comparison do not provide explicit data\non code density, or heterogeneous memory usage, which\nlimits the scope of metric-level comparison. Therefore, our\nevaluation focuses on the implementation structure, and exe-\ncution efﬁciency of these frameworks. Table II presents the\nimplementation results of various CNNs across different archi-\ntectures, comparing their performance and resource utilization\nmetrics. While the table highlights speciﬁc CNNs, such as\nYOLOv3-Tiny, YOLOv5s, ResNet50, and MNIST, it is impor-\ntant to note that the proposed compilation framework is not\nrestricted to these models. It is designed to support a wide\nrange of CNNs, showcasing its general-purpose capability in\nhandling diverse neural networks.\nOur architecture, which is based on the RISC-V RV32IM\nCPU and a custom NPU, supports multiple CNNs, as shown\nin the results presented in the rightmost column. The NPU is\ncapable of executing all the operators from these networks,\nwhile the CPU primarily handles instruction recognition and\ndistribution. This design signiﬁcantly reduces network latency,\nresulting in excellent performance. The architecture is ver-\nsatile, supporting model execution with both high and low\nprecision (from 32-bit to 8-bit) while maintaining consistent\nperformance levels. For instance, when deploying YOLOv3\nand ResNet50, we achieve competitive performance with\n8-bit quantization, allowing for reduced memory footprint\nand improved computational efﬁciency without signiﬁcantly\nsacriﬁcing accuracy. This ﬂexibility in precision allows the\narchitecture to adapt to various deployment requirements, from\nhigh-accuracy models, such as ResNet50, to more lightweight,\nreal-time models, such as YOLOv3-Tiny. It is worth noting\nthat the operators executed on the CPU maintain a 32-bit\nprecision to ensure computational accuracy. Therefore, latency\ncomparisons are made while accounting for any additional\ndelays introduced by high-precision processing on the CPU,\nwhere applicable.\nIn comparison to other architectures listed in the table,\nsuch as the extended SODA synthesizer in [14], our archi-\ntecture excels in delivering lower memory footprints (e.g.,\n24.4 MB for ResNet50 compared to 97.7 MB in [14]) and\nreduced latency (e.g., 56.7 ms for ResNet50 compared to\n1614.8 ms in [14]) even converted to 32-bit precision. At\nthe same time, our latency is also 11.2× faster than that\nIEEE TRANSACTIONS ON COMPUTER-AIDED DESIGN OF INTEGRATED CIRCUITS AND SYSTEMS, VOL. 44, NO. 11, NOVEMBER 2025\nFig. 6.\nComparison of code density and inference time for task scheduler evaluation. (a) Code density comparison in the USER_DEFINE mode. (b) Inference\ntime comparison in the USER_DEFINE mode. (c) Code density comparison in the DEFAULT mode. (d) Inference time comparison in the DEFAULT mode.\nin [18] at the same precision and low frequency. Regarding\nYOLOv3-Tiny, while [12] adopts 32-bit numerical precision,\nour implementation in 8-bit quantization achieves a latency of\nmore than one-fourth of theirs. This discrepancy arises because\nthe accelerator in [12] is speciﬁcally designed for YOLOv3-\nTiny, and our implementation involves data transformation on\nthe CPU with 32-bit precision. Consequently, the ﬁnal latency\naligns with expectations. Finally, MNIST, as a representative\nDNN, is also included in our evaluation. However, the speedup\nis not particularly signiﬁcant, as only the Gemm and ReLU\noperators can be ofﬂoaded to the NPU for computation.\nHowever, our architecture is capable of supporting the full\nrange of DNN computations.\nIt is worth noting that the compilation time in our framework\nis on the order of minutes, as it involves multilevel dialect\noptimizations and complex ﬁxed-point quantization and rear-\nrangement of weights. However, in practical scenarios, this\noverhead is negligible since precompilation does not impact\nthe runtime computational efﬁciency.\nB. Task Scheduler Evaluation\nIn the task scheduling strategy, we offer three modes to\nmanage the assignment of operations between the CPU and\nthe NPU based on user-speciﬁc requirements. The efﬁciency\nof each mode is veriﬁed as shown in Fig. 6. The experiments\nfocus on two metrics: 1) code density and 2) inference time.\nThese metrics are unaffected by memory management because\nmemory allocation follows a ﬁxed strategy throughout task\nscheduling experiments. Hence, the differences observed in\ntask scheduling conﬁgurations can be attributed solely to\nscheduling strategies.\nAll_CPU Mode: In this mode, we run YOLOv3-Tiny with\nan input size of 224 × 224 × 3 (in 8-bit), and observed an\nextraordinarily high cycle count of 277 billion cycles. One\nreason for this high cycle count may be that the RV32IM ISA\nlacks the specialized hardware extensions needed for efﬁcient\ndeep learning workloads. Many modern architectures leverage\nsingle instruction, multiple data (SIMD), vector operations, or\ndedicated accelerators to speed up the matrix multiplications\nand convolutions, which are common in deep learning tasks.\nSince the RV32IM ISA does not include these features, the\nprocessor likely needs to execute more instructions to achieve\nthe same results, further contributing to the high cycle count.\nSecond, a small cache can lead to frequent misses, forcing\nthe processor to access slower main memory more often.\nYOLOv3-Tiny involves many convolutions that repeatedly\naccess input features, weights, and intermediate results. If the\ncache is too small to hold this data across layers, the CPU\nspends more time waiting on memory, increasing the cycle\ncount.\nBased on the above analysis, there are two key approaches\nfor our architecture to enhance the CPU inference speed. First,\nwe can customize the instruction set for deep learning tasks;\nsecond, a larger cache is needed. Additionally, we tested the\nnetwork with an input size of 224 × 256 × 3 to simulate\npadding in cols operation mentioned in Section V-B, which\ntakes around 278 billion cycles, very close to the time taken\nwithout padding. This indicates that the additional overhead\nof the CPU to accommodate NPU computation is negligible.\nUSER_DEFINE Mode: In this mode, we tested how\ndividing tasks affects performance, to illustrate the feasibility\nof this mode. Fig. 6(a) and (b) provides a detailed comparison\nCAO et al.: HETEROGENEOUS CNN COMPILATION FRAMEWORK\nof code density and inference time across four different CNN\nmodels. Code density is chosen as a key metric because it\naffects storage efﬁciency, power consumption, and execution\nperformance. Lower code density reduces memory usage,\nlowers power by minimizing accesses, and improves efﬁciency\nby requiring fewer instructions. Each model is evaluated\nunder ﬁve scenarios, representing varying proportions of tasks\nofﬂoaded to the NPU, denoted by O_P, ranging from 0 (no\nofﬂoading) to 1 (complete ofﬂoading).\nThe results indicate a clear trend: as the proportion of tasks\nofﬂoaded to the NPU increases, the code density and inference\ntime decrease. For each network, the highest code density\nand inference time occurs when no tasks are ofﬂoaded (O_P\n= 0), with signiﬁcant reductions noted as more tasks are\nofﬂoaded to the NPU. Notably, YOLOv3 exhibits the highest\ncode density across all tested models, starting from over 30 000\nlines in the baseline case. At the same time, due to RISC-V’s\ncomputational inefﬁciency, it also has the highest latency at\nO_P = 0, up to 13 234 ms. As the ofﬂoading proportion\nincreases, there is a signiﬁcant decline in code density and\ninference time, highlighting the potential efﬁciency gains.\nResNet50 and ResNet34 exhibit a similar trend, they have\nlower overall code densities and inference time compared to\nYOLOv3. YOLOv3-Tiny also shows a decrease in code den-\nsity and inference time, but the reduction is less pronounced\ncompared to that of the full YOLOv3 model. This suggests\nthat larger and more complex networks experience greater\nbeneﬁts from the tasks ofﬂoading. Overall, this ﬁgure under-\nscores the effectiveness of task ofﬂoading in reducing code\ndensity and inference time, which is a critical factor in opti-\nmizing computational performance on resource-constrained\nplatforms.\nDEFAULT Mode: In this mode, we evaluated the impact\nof ofﬂoading different types of operators to the NPU on the\ncode density and inference time of various CNN models. As\nshown in Fig. 6(c) and (d), 1 × 1 convolutions, 3 × 3 con-\nvolutions, and convolutions with following element-additions\nare ofﬂoaded to the NPU, repectively. ResNet50 and ResNet34\nexhibit a similar trend in code density and inference time\nreduction. They start with a relatively high code density and\ninference time on the CPU, which decreases consistently as\nmore operations are ofﬂoaded. The most pronounced reduction\noccurs when 3 × 3 convolutions are ofﬂoaded, indicating\ntheir computational intensity. This trend is particularly notable\nin ResNet34, which contains a greater number of 3 × 3\nconvolutions than 1 × 1 convolutions. YOLOv3 shows the\nhighest code density and inference time in the all_CPU mode\nbut experiences substantial beneﬁts from separately ofﬂoading\nboth 1 × 1 and 3 × 3 convolutions. YOLOv3-Tiny, as a more\nlightly weighted model, also displays a reduction pattern simi-\nlar to the larger networks, despite having an overall lower code\ndensity and inference time. Since this model does not have an\nelement-addition layer, ofﬂoading the Conv+Add operations\nis useless. Overall, this analysis underscores the efﬁciency\ngains achieved by selectively ofﬂoading speciﬁc types of\noperators to the NPU, particularly highlighting the advantages\nfor in-depth examinations of heterogeneous computational\nplatforms.\nFig. 7.\nComparison of FM memory usage across different NPU memory\nallocation strategies. (* indicates that the self-checking function in the DE\nmechanism is active).\nC. Memory Efﬁciency Evaluation\nTo evaluate the independent impact of memory management\nstrategies, we conduct all experiments in the ALL_NPU\nmode to eliminate interference from task scheduling. We\ncompare three memory allocation mechanisms implemented\nin the NPU: 1) DE; 2) RU; and 3) sequential storage (SS).\nSince task scheduling is ﬁxed in this mode, variations in\nmemory usage reﬂect purely the contribution of memory\nmanagement strategies. The experiments aimes to assess the\nmemory consumption of FMs (the input FM size is 224 ×\n224×3) across different mechanisms, with results summarized\nin Fig. 7.\nAmong the three mechanisms, SS consumes the most\nmemory across all models. For instance, ResNet50 and\nYOLOv3 have memory demands of 11.00 MB and 12.51 MB,\nrespectively, while VGG16 requires 9.99 MB when using SS.\nThis is because SS stores all intermediate results without any\nreuse or optimization. In addition to this, this mechanism leads\nto a direct link between memory and model size, with large\ngaps in memory between different models. For example, in\nthe tested models, the minimum FM memory size is 1.14 MB,\nwhile the maximum reaches 12.51 MB.\nThe RU mechanism shows a notable reduction in memory\nusage compared to SS. Speciﬁcally, memory usage for\nResNet50 decreases from 11.00 MB (SS) to 2.41 MB (RU),\nwhile YOLOv3 shows a reduction from 12.51 MB (SS) to\n2.84 MB (RU). However, although RU improves efﬁciency, it\nstill consumes more memory than DE, as it reuses allocated\nmemory less aggressively in some models.\nDE stands out as the most efﬁcient memory allocation\nmechanism, reducing memory consumption to minimal levels.\nFor example, ResNet50 requires only 1.97 MB, achieving a\n5.58× reduction compared to SS. The DE mechanism dynam-\nically releases memory that is no longer required for future\noperations, leading to a signiﬁcant decrease in FM memory\nusage. In addition, the self-checking function discussed in\nSection VI-C has been validated in ResNet34 and ResNet50,\nas the original memory allocation in the DE mechanism may\nnot be sufﬁcient for models with branching paths.\nUsing either DE or RU mechanisms, the difference in FM\nmemory required between the different networks is much\nIEEE TRANSACTIONS ON COMPUTER-AIDED DESIGN OF INTEGRATED CIRCUITS AND SYSTEMS, VOL. 44, NO. 11, NOVEMBER 2025\nsmaller, generally under 5 MB. The optimization results for\nthese two mechanisms show little variation, and in some cases,\nsuch as ResNet34 and YOLOv3-Tiny, their effects are virtually\nidentical. Therefore, to simplify the compilation process, users\ncan opt for the more straightforward RU mechanism.\nVIII. CONCLUSION AND FUTURE WORKS\nIn this article, we propose a compilation framework based\non RISC-V CPU/NPU co-computing to address the challenge\nof mapping and compiling from algorithms to heterogeneous\narchitectures. By integrating custom operator packing, a ver-\nsatile task scheduler, and optimized memory management, the\nproposed framework signiﬁcantly enhances the efﬁciency and\nperformance of heterogeneous architectures. Our experimental\nresults demonstrate that the framework can effectively gen-\nerate optimized instructions for various models, signiﬁcantly\nenhancing the efﬁciency and performance of heterogeneous\narchitectures. It achieves up to a 7.06× reduction in code\ndensity and up to a 5.58× improvement in memory usage,\nbridging the computational gap between CPUs and NPUs.\nMoving forward, we could explore the integration of more\nadvanced machine learning models, such as transformers, and\ntheir adaptation to more heterogeneous architectures. This will\nbe part of our future work.",
